 type of value (positive, neutral, and negative).  The instructor would use a \\\'reinforcer survey\\\' or a preference assessment to determine what has value.  If the instructor does not have adequate valued stimuli she conditions objects, activities, or instructor actions as potentially reinforcing stimuli.  The process of conditioning stimuli as potentially reinforcing stimuli involves pairing and/or correlating neutral stimuli with \\\'known\\\' reinforcing stimuli.  The value of stimuli may vary throughout the day. I believe that Catania would have classified conditioning stimuli under the behavioral operation \\\'Stimulus Control\\\' but I\\\'ve taken the liberty of classify it under \\\'Presenting Stimuli\\\'.\r\n', 'Basic Behavior Operations', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21207023\":\"12.07b3\"}}'), ('855', 'PREVAILING STIMULI', 'One factor that may affect the development or weakening of repertoires\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 12', '{\"12\":{\"2120402\":\"12.04b\"}}'), ('856', 'PRIMARY REINFORCERS', 'Things that humans are born to value\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 7', '{\"7\":{\"1710041\":\"7.10d1\",\"1710042\":\"7.10d2\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190005020\":\"9A.05f2\"}}'), ('857', 'Prime, Prompt, Fade and Reinforce', 'A prime involves telling or showing someone exactly what to do or say.  May be able to avoid shaping new behavior if the learner\\\'s behavior can be primed.  When a teacher prompts a learner to perform a desired behavior, s/he is providing a level of assistance that is necessary for the learner to be successful.  A prompt is an antecedent in that it sets the occasion for the behavior to occur.  A prompt is an \\\'additional\\\' stimulus that MUST be faded in order for the L  to respond under the desired stimulus conditions.  Fading is the gradual change of the antecedent(s) controlling  the behavior, such that the behavior eventually occurs to a partially changed or completely  new stimulus condition.  In any situation in which a stimulus exerts strong control over a behavior,  fading can be a very useful procedure for changing the stimulus control.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"9A L4\":{\"190005080\":\"9A.05g5\"}}'), ('858', 'PROMPT', 'Level of assistance required for learner\\\'s success\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 1', '{\"2\":{\"1202081\":\"2.02h1\"},\"4\":{\"1406023\":\"4.06b3\"},\"5\":{\"150407\":\"5.04g\",\"1506041\":\"5.06d1\"},\"9b\":{\"1903024\":\"9.03b4\"},\"12\":{\"21205013\":\"12.05a3\",\"21205023\":\"12.05b3\",\"21207065\":\"12.07f5\",\"21207066\":\"12.07f6\",\"21207071\":\"12.07g1\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001260\":\"9A.04f3\",\"190001160\":\"9A.04e2\",\"190001180\":\"9A.04e4\",\"190001150\":\"9A.04e1\",\"190000810\":\"9A.03k2\",\"190000210\":\"9A.01c5\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004860\":\"9A.05c5\",\"190004940\":\"9A.05e1\",\"190004950\":\"9A.05e2\",\"190004960\":\"9A.05e3\",\"190004970\":\"9A.05e4\",\"190004980\":\"9A.05e5\",\"190004990\":\"9A.05e6\",\"190005000\":\"9A.05e7 \",\"190005010\":\"9A.05f1\",\"190005050\":\"9A.05g2\",\"190004935\":\"9A.05d5\"},\"\":{\"118130\":\"2pt.02h1\"}}'), ('859', 'Punishment', 'If in a given situation a person is \\\'less likely\\\' to engage in behavior that has been followed by a certain consequence then we say that the consequence is a punisher.  Punishment lessens the likelihood that the person will do it again under similar circumstances.  Does not mean that he will NEVER do it again.  There are a number of potentially harmful side-effects from punishment procedures.  Must have evidence that reinforcement contingencies alone were not effective in weakening the undesired repertoire(s).  Must always  be used in concert with reinforcement procedures.  Once you implement a punishment procedure, you must deliver it EVERY time for it to remain effective (hard work).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Weaken', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21203021\":\"12.03b1\",\"21208\":\"12.08a\"},\"\":{\"80409218\":\"DI_218\"}}'), ('860', 'Quick Transfer Procedure for Verbal Behavior', 'Quick Transfer  involves presenting ALL the stimuli that control VERBAL BEHAVIOR (e.g., vocalizing or signing) and fading one of the  controlling stimuli (prompts) at a time.  For instance, L will say \\\"candy\\\" when candy is displayed and he wants candy.  Begin to transfer the control to echoic conditions by gradually fading the presence of candy; start with the candy in \\\'full sight\\\' of  L &amp; fade its presence until it is \\\'out of sight\\\' of  L.  At any step when L does not perform successfully, move back to the previous step where the L was successful (i.e., top of candy in sight of learner).  In summary, begin initial sessions by making sure L wants candy.  If he asks for candy give it to him initially.  If it appears he still \\\'wants\\\' candy then proceed to transfer the control to echoic conditions. For example, T says, \\\'Say candy\\\' with candy displayed. If  L  says \\\"Candy\\\" then proceed to gradually fade the presence of candy.  Transfer  is successful when the learner says \\\"Candy\\\" without the presence of  it (i.e., candy is NOT displayed and L does NOT get candy when he says candy; pure echoic behavior).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21207065\":\"12.07f5\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006950\":\"9A.05p1\"}}'), ('852', 'Premack Principle', 'The Premack procedure is often referred to as the Grandma\\\'s Law,  \\\"As soon as you finish your homework then you can watch TV  for an hour.\\\"  In order for the contingency to remain effective it is important to: a) provide a variety of preferred tasks, activities or items and  b) gradually increase the length of time the learner is expected to participate in the assigned tasks or the number of tasks that the learner must complete in order to access the reinforcer (preferred tasks, items, or activities).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006880\":\"9A.05o1\",\"190006890\":\"9A.05o2\"}}'), ('853', 'Premack Principle-Independent Group Contingency', 'The Premack procedure is often referred to as the Grandma\\\'s Law,  \\\"As soon as you finish your homework then you can watch TV for an hour.\\\"   In order for the contingency to remain effective it is important to: a) provide a variety of preferred tasks, activities or items and  b) gradually increase the length of time the learner is expected to participate in the assigned tasks or the number of tasks that the learner must complete in order to access the reinforcer (preferred tasks, items or activities).  It may be best  for naive learners to arrange independent group contingencies - some members of the group may earn reinforcer(s) while others may  have access to reinforcers delayed until s/he meets criteria.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '[]'), ('851', 'Positive Reinforcement', 'If in a given situation somebody does something that is followed immediately by a certain consequence, then that person is more likely to do the same thing again when he next encounters a similar situation.  NEW responses are reinforced immediately every time (i.e., continuous schedule of reinforcement [crf]).  FIRM responses are reinforced immediately intermittently [int]).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21203031\":\"12.03c 1\",\"21203032\":\"12.03c2\",\"21203033\":\"12.03c3\",\"21203034\":\"12.03c4\",\"21203042\":\"12.03d2\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001470\":\"9A.04i3\",\"190000820\":\"9A.03k3\",\"190000830\":\"9A.03k4\",\"190000670\":\"9A.03h3\",\"190000660\":\"9A.03h2\",\"190000550\":\"9A.03f6\",\"190000520\":\"9A.03f3\",\"190000500\":\"9A.03f1\",\"190000510\":\"9A.03f2\",\"190000110\":\"9A.01b2\"},\"\":{\"80409223\":\"DI_223\",\"80409225\":\"DI_225\",\"32100803\":\"210.08c\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004760\":\"9A.05b5\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006830\":\"9A.05n2\"}}'), ('850', 'POSITIVE EXAMPLES', 'Examples of one and only one distinguishing quality of the concept\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 9', '{\"9b\":{\"1901024\":\"9.01b4\",\"1901025\":\"9.01b5\",\"1901042\":\"9.01d2\",\"1901055\":\"9.01e5\",\"1901063\":\"9.01f3\",\"1901071\":\"9.01g1\",\"1901101\":\"9.01j1\",\"1901121\":\"9.01l1\",\"1901122\":\"9.01l2\",\"1902011\":\"9.02a1\",\"1903021\":\"9.03b1\",\"1903022\":\"9.03b2\",\"1903023\":\"9.03b3\",\"1903036\":\"9.03c6\",\"1903037\":\"9.03c7\"}}'), ('846', 'PAIRING STIMULI', 'Associating neutral stimuli with known reinforcing&nbsp;stimuli\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 7', '{\"7\":{\"1705011\":\"7.05a1\",\"1705043\":\"7.05d3\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000400\":\"9A.03d2\",\"190000390\":\"9A.03d1\"}}'), ('847', 'Participator Curriculum: Lesson 1-33', 'Created for our learners that may have nearly all of the CLM repertoires, but do not value instruction.  They may also have basic understanding of some academic standards.  For example, they may know all their numbers up to 100, all of their ABC\\\'s but will not perform in any type of instructional condition.  With this curriculum we can focus on improving the value of teacher-directed, semi-directed, peer-directed, non-directed participation.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('848', 'Performance Assessment:Competent Learner Repertoire Assessments (CLRA) ', 'Within the CLM, these assessments are called the \\\"Competent Learner Repertoire Assessments or CLRAs for Learners. Primarily, the CLRA is used to determine the repertoires that are \\\'missing\\\' and to track the learners\\\' progress through the CLM Curriculum.  The CLRAs assist educators to appropriately place a learner in validated curricula by providing a profile of the learner\\\'s strengths and weaknesses across seven key \\\"learning-to-learn\\\" repertoires (i.e., CLRs, see 1, above). The CLRA has been shown to have concurrent validity with the Vineland Adaptive Behavior Scales, be sensitive to change in learner behavior, and have high inter-observer agreement among educators using it to assess their learners.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('849', 'Performance Assessment: Implementation Accountability Process (IAP)', 'The intent of the IAP is to assure that everyone on the \\\'Site Team\\\' knows what\\\'s happening in a given setting and who\\\'s responsible for the tasks. Therefore, phases have been developed to \\\'label\\\' what tasks should be completed and by whom (e.g., Teacher, District Administrator and Regional Associate). This way everyone knows exacting what they\\\'re priorities are for implementing the CLModel. The IAP checklist consists of a startup phase and four additional phases. There are some \\\'common tasks\\\' that occur during each phase for the Teacher, Instructional Aides, Coordinator, Coach, Collaborative Consultant (BCBA) and District Administrator: 1) Setup a specific type of classroom schedule. 2) Complete CLM Units.3) Collect specific type of data on particular forms.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('832', 'Generalized Conditioned Reinforcement (e.g., Tokens or Points)', 'Conditioned reinforcers have special features.   They are effective across all conditions.   They remain effective because they lead to access of  a variety of  \\\"back-up\\\" reinforcers (e.g., food or activities).   These conditioned reinforcers are called generalized conditioned reinforcers (e.g., money, attention,  and approval).  If a learner has satiated on one type of reinforcer, he is  still  going to \\\"want\\\" another type of reinforcer that he has been deprived of.  The more conspicuous the reinforcement contingency the more effective it can be.  Tokens, pennies, or points are often used for this reason.  In order to be effective they must be conditioned as reinforcers (see the \\\'Conditioning Neutral Stimuli as Reinforcers\\\'contingency).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '[]'), ('833', 'GETTING BEHAVIORS', 'Type of behaviors used to gain what is wanted\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 6', '{\"3\":{\"130307190507101\":\"3.03g(seg1)a\"},\"\":{\"128270\":\"3pt.03g(seg1)a\"}}'), ('834', 'HELP', 'Assistance provided when learner has unexpect