l performance of the newly established repertoire or responses.\r\nGeneralization routines are used to strengthen existing repertoires or responses by \'bringing the behavior under control of novel stimulus conditions\'. When you develop the competent learner repertoires you want your learner to perform across people, places, and items.\r\nThe process of generalization may involve the instructor arranging a rearranging a dimension or aspect of the controlling stimuli (antecedents and consequences). Well-designed teaching sequences provide the necessary arrangements of the antecedents; yet, they greatly impact how often you can deliver consequences. If arranged properly, the learner will continue to perform under the NEW stimulus conditions.\r\nIn their text, Theory of Instruction, Englemann and Carnine (1982, p 173) suggest several expansion activities (generalization routine).  For example, the instructor may have used an acquisition routine (initial teaching sequence; non-comparative) to teach the concept \'on\' and wants the learner to use the concept under novel circumstances (i.e., different setup and wording).\r\nFor example, the instructor may have used an acquisition routine (initial teaching sequence; non-comparative) to teach the concept \'on\' and wants the learner to use the concept under novel circumstances (i.e., different setup and wording).  In the teaching sequence, the instructor used the set up of a block on the table and used the wording, \'The block is on the table\'.   In the generalization routine, the instructor may use a different but similar setup, a balloon on a chair, and similar wording, \'The balloon is on the chair.\r\nEnglemann and Carnine (1982, 1990) suggest that after the first or second initial teaching sequence (acquisition routine), an instructor should practice the newly firmed item in an expansion activity (generalization routine), particularly with single-dimension concepts like \'on\'.\r\nAnother example of an expansion activity is the \'Fooler Game\'.  The instructor makes purposeful mistakes with the new concept or verbal association and tells the learner to say, \"Stop\", if the instructor makes a mistake.  For example, when expanding the concept of \'on\', the instructor places the balloon under the chair and the learner says \'Stop\'.  When the instructor places the balloon \'on\' the chair, the learner does not say anything.  Learners are likely to enjoy these \'Fooler games\' since they get to \'catch\' the instructor in a mistake.\r\nHere is another example of generalization routine with a different repertoire.  If your learner will participate when you are seated next to him (at-hand) then you would gradually change your proximity from at hand (1 foot) to far away (7 feet away).  By doing so, you are bringing participation under the control of new stimulus conditions. When you alter the existing stimulus conditions you must assure for a gradual change in the existing stimulus dimension you are altering.\r\nRemember, be sure and fade any prompts within the session, if possible. You may have to provide a richer schedule of reinforcement initially but lean the schedule ASAP.\r\nOnce you\'ve selected the type of expansion activity (e.g., Fooler game), you must set up a schedule to practice the newly learned concept.  For example, if you teach the concept of \'on\' in the first and second session, you would schedule the first expansion activity at the end of the second session.  You may alternate the type of expansion activities.  DO NOT attempt an expansion activity unless the learner\'s response is NEWLY firmed. You have demonstrated via the test examples that the learner \'understands\' the concept being taught.  Repeat this practice schedule with other new concepts.\r\nOnce you teach an additional concept (e.g.,\'over\'), practiced it by itself.  Next use a discrimination routine to strengthen the NEWly firmed concept with the previously learned concept (e.g., \'on\'). For an example of the guidelines for another routine for the generalization of verbal behavior, refer to WorkSheets for Designing Contingencies and find the one called, \'Quick Transfer Procedure for Verbal Behavior\'.\r\n', 'Instructional Routines', '', '', '{\"9b\":{\"1901022\":\"9.01b2\",\"1901042\":\"9.01d2\",\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\",\"190105202\":\"9.01e2b\",\"1901056\":\"9.01e6\",\"1901059\":\"9.01e9\",\"1901101\":\"9.01j1\",\"1901103\":\"9.01j3\",\"1901111\":\"9.01k1\",\"1901112\":\"9.01k2\"},\"12\":{\"21207061\":\"12.07f1\",\"21207067\":\"12.07f7\",\"21207069\":\"12.07f9\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006910\":\"9A.05o4\",\"190006920\":\"9A.05o5\",\"190006950\":\"9A.05p1\"}}'), ('827', 'Fluency Based Instruction', 'The teacher selects an already established skill for the learner to \\\'practice.\\\'  The teacher identifies the previous \\\'best performance\\\' the learner attained on that skill.  Based on the data, the teacher sets a goal for the learner to reach during that day\\\'s practice on the skill.  Practice sessions occur each day.  The teacher schedules time for the learner to complete as many practices as needed to meet the goal the teacher has established for that day.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21207053\":\"12.07e3\"}}'), ('825', 'FIRM TASK', 'Task that can be performed without assistance\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 1', '{\"1\":{\"110703\":\"1.07c\",\"1108\":\"1.08\",\"1110\":\"1.10\",\"1111011\":\"1.11a1\",\"111301\":\"1.13a\",\"1113021\":\"1.13b1\",\"1113022\":\"1.13b2\",\"1109\":\"1.09\"},\"2\":{\"120201\":\"2.02a\",\"120301\":\"2.03a\",\"1203022\":\"2.03b2\"},\"5\":{\"150403\":\"5.04c\",\"1504051\":\"5.04e1\",\"1504052\":\"5.04e2\",\"150407\":\"5.04g\",\"150501\":\"5.05a\",\"1506041\":\"5.06d1\"},\"8\":{\"180603\":\"8.06c\",\"180803\":\"8.08c\"},\"9b\":{\"1901022\":\"9.01b2\",\"190105202\":\"9.01e2b\",\"1901056\":\"9.01e6\",\"1901103\":\"9.01j3\",\"1901105\":\"9.01j5\",\"1901111\":\"9.01k1\",\"1903011\":\"9.03a1\",\"1903031\":\"9.03c1\",\"1903032\":\"9.03c2\",\"1903033\":\"9.03c3\",\"1903034\":\"9.03c4\",\"1903035\":\"9.03c5\",\"1905011\":\"9.05a1\",\"1905012\":\"9.05a2\"},\"11\":{\"2110703505\":\"11.07c5A\",\"21108011\":\"11.08a1\"},\"12\":{\"21203022\":\"12.03b2\",\"21203033\":\"12.03c3\",\"21207011\":\"12.07a1\",\"21207035\":\"12.07c5\",\"21207036\":\"12.07c6\",\"21207045\":\"12.07d5\",\"21207051\":\"12.07e1\",\"21207052\":\"12.07e2\",\"21207053\":\"12.07e3\",\"21207054\":\"12.07e4\",\"21207055\":\"12.07e5\",\"21207056\":\"12.07e6\",\"21207057\":\"12.07e7\",\"21207064\":\"12.07f4\",\"21207071\":\"12.07g1\",\"21207073\":\"12.07g3\",\"21207085\":\"12.07h5\",\"21207086\":\"12.07h6\"},\"100\":{\"310007013\":\"100.07a3\",\"310007014\":\"100.07a4\",\"310007021\":\"100.07b1\",\"310007022\":\"100.07b2\",\"310007023\":\"100.07b3\",\"310007024\":\"100.07b4\",\"310007025\":\"100.07b5\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001270\":\"9A.04f4\",\"190001280\":\"9A.04f5\",\"190001250\":\"9A.04f2\",\"190001240\":\"9A.04f1\",\"190001170\":\"9A.04e3\",\"190001090\":\"9A.04c7\",\"190000930\":\"9A.04a2\",\"190000920\":\"9A.04a1\",\"190000200\":\"9A.01c4\",\"190000130\":\"9A.01b4\",\"190000020\":\"9A.01a2\"},\"\":{\"80409222\":\"DI_222\",\"109150\":\"1pt.07c\",\"118050\":\"2pt.02a\",\"109180\":\"1pt.10\",\"109190\":\"1pt.11a1\",\"1091205\":\"1pt.06a\",\"1091206\":\"1pt.06b1\",\"1091207\":\"1pt.06b2\",\"118160\":\"2pt.03a\",\"118180\":\"2pt.03b2\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004670\":\"9A.05a2\",\"190004680\":\"9A.05a3\",\"190004690\":\"9A.05a4\",\"190004700\":\"9A.05a5\",\"190004730\":\"9A.05b3a\",\"190004740\":\"9A.05b3b\",\"190004870\":\"9A.05c6\",\"190004880\":\"9A.05c8\",\"190004980\":\"9A.05e5\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006680\":\"9A.05k8\",\"190006850\":\"9A.05n5\",\"190006890\":\"9A.05o2\"}}'), ('826', 'Fluency', 'Fluency routines are used to strengthen existing repertoires or firmed responses. Fluency is a \\\'Stimulus Control\\\' operation; it includes manipulation of the antecedent and the consequences.\r\nThe instructor selects an already established skill for the learner to \\\'practice\\\'. The instructor identifies the previous \\\'best performance\\\' the learner attained on that skill. Based on those data, the instructor sets a goal for the learner to reach during that day\\\'s practice on the skill. Practice sessions occur each day for a set period of time, say 15 seconds.  Practice session should be short (e.g., 10 seconds) to start with and gradually lengthened to longer and longer periods until each session last up to 60 seconds.  The instructor schedules time for the learner to complete as many practices as needed to meet the goal the instructor has established for that day. When the learner meets the goal the instructor has set for that day, the instructor delivers a reward and the learner moves on to the next activity in their schedule.\r\nThe instructor places the materials for the selected skill (labeling pictures) in front of the learner (e.g., several pictures of different dogs, birds, cats, &amp; fishes). At the beginning of each practice session the instructor says, \\\"Tell the names of these pictures as fast as you can\\\'. Instructor starts the timer as soon as the learner begins to respond. The learner says the names of the animals as fast as they can until the timer stops.  Always have more items on display than the Learner could possible respond to in the allotted time interval.  This is important so the Learner does not run out of material to respond to. The instructor has the student complete as many \\\'timings\\\' (practice) as needed to beat their previous best performance.\r\nRefer to WorkSheets for Designing Contingencies for the guidelines/steps for \\\'Fluency Based Instruction\\\".\r\n', 'Instructional Routines', '', '', '{\"9b\":{\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\",\"1903035\":\"9.03c5\"},\"12\":{\"21207053\":\"12.07e3\"},\"100\":{\"310007012\":\"100.07a2\",\"310007014\":\"100.07a4\"},\"\":{\"32100101\":\"210.01a\",\"32100102\":\"210.01b\",\"32100103\":\"210.01c\",\"321009