to identify the source of reinforcement that is maintaining the behavior.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Weaken', '', '', '{\"2\":{\"1210054\":\"2.10e4\",\"121006\":\"2.10f\"},\"4\":{\"1403031\":\"4.03c1\"},\"10\":{\"21011062\":\"10.11f2\"},\"12\":{\"21203021\":\"12.03b1\",\"21207062\":\"12.07f2\",\"21208\":\"12.08a\",\"2120802\":\"12.08b\",\"2120805\":\"12.08e\",\"2120806\":\"12.08f\",\"2120811\":\"12.08k\",\"2120812\":\"12.08l\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001220\":\"9A.04e8\",\"190001200\":\"9A.04e6\",\"190001110\":\"9A.04c9\",\"190001080\":\"9A.04c6\"},\"\":{\"118510\":\"2pt.10e4\",\"118520\":\"2pt.10f\"}}'), ('824', 'FAULTLESS COMMUNICATION', 'Teaching sequence that eliminates confusion\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 9', '{\"9b\":{\"1901023\":\"9.01b3\"}}'), ('819', 'Echoic', 'A verbal response to a verbal stimulus that has point-to-point correspondence (that is, repeating exactly what is heard).\r\n', 'Verbal Operants', '', '', '{\"1\":{\"110702\":\"1.07b\",\"110703\":\"1.07c\",\"1108\":\"1.08\",\"1109\":\"1.09\"},\"4\":{\"1401013\":\"4.01a3\",\"1401021\":\"4.01b1\",\"140707\":\"4.07g\"},\"8\":{\"1801011\":\"8.01a1\",\"180802\":\"8.08b\"},\"11\":{\"21104016\":\"11.04a6\"},\"12\":{\"21205012\":\"12.05a2\",\"21205014\":\"12.05a4\",\"21205015\":\"12.05a5\",\"21205016\":\"12.05a6\",\"21207051\":\"12.07e1\",\"21207054\":\"12.07e4\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001390\":\"9A.04h2\",\"190001330\":\"9A.04g5\",\"190001320\":\"9A.04g4\",\"190001290\":\"9A.04g1\",\"190001300\":\"9A.04g2\",\"190000930\":\"9A.04a2\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004680\":\"9A.05a3\",\"190004810\":\"9A.05c1a\",\"190004820\":\"9A.05c1b\",\"190005100\":\"9A.05g7\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006860\":\"9A.05n6\",\"190006950\":\"9A.05p1\",\"190006960\":\"9A.05p2A\",\"190006990\":\"9A.05p4A\",\"190007000\":\"9A.05p4B\",\"190007010\":\"9A.05p5A\",\"190007040\":\"9A.05p7\",\"190007060\":\"9A.05p8B\"},\"\":{\"109140\":\"1pt.07b\",\"109150\":\"1pt.07c\"}}'), ('818', 'Discrimination', 'Discrimination routines are used to bring the learner\\\'s responding under the control of the desired stimulus conditions. Discrimination routines are used to strengthen NEWly firmed responses, therefore, strengthening existing repertoires. They are \\\'Stimulus Control\\\' operations.  They include manipulation of the antecedents and the consequences.\r\nDiscrimination routines \\\'bring newly firmed responses under the control of a particular stimulus\\\'. We reinforce correct responding in the presence of the desired stimulus (e.g. Learner says \\\'dog\\\' ONLY when a picture of a  \\\'dog\\\' is present).\r\nYou must return to the acquisition routine if not successful during the discrimination routine.\r\nDuring the discrimination routine, you must reinforce the learner\\\'s responding more and more intermittently at each step of development. For example, the instructor reinforces about every 3rd response then 5th response and then about every 7th correct response, etc.  Overtime you will randomly present all items, newly firmed (X) and firmed (A), until the learner can perform as expected under the desired stimulus conditions before moving on to the next routine.\r\nThe instructor is expected to use the NEWly firmed and firm items in the other remaining instructional routines.  Englemann and Carnine (1982, 1990) suggest that the initial teaching concepts should be practiced using a generalization routine, as soon as possible.    Refer to the CLM Curriculum for the precise discrimination routine per repertoire in the form of formats.\r\n', 'Instructional Routines', '', '', '{\"9b\":{\"1901022\":\"9.01b2\",\"1901034\":\"9.01c4\",\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\",\"190105301\":\"9.01e3a\",\"190105302\":\"9.01e3b\",\"1901056\":\"9.01e6\",\"1901057\":\"9.01e7\",\"1901059\":\"9.01e9\",\"1901064\":\"9.01f4\",\"1901074\":\"9.01g4\",\"1901101\":\"9.01j1\",\"1901111\":\"9.01k1\",\"1901112\":\"9.01k2\",\"1903031\":\"9.03c1\",\"1903032\":\"9.03c2\",\"1903033\":\"9.03c3\",\"1903035\":\"9.03c5\",\"1903036\":\"9.03c6\",\"190401\":\"9.04a\",\"190402\":\"9.04b\",\"1905011\":\"9.05a1\",\"190601\":\"9.06a\"},\"12\":{\"21207061\":\"12.07f1\",\"21207062\":\"12.07f2\",\"21207069\":\"12.07f9\",\"21207073\":\"12.07g3\"},\"100\":{\"310007014\":\"100.07a4\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001270\":\"9A.04f4\",\"190001280\":\"9A.04f5\",\"190001260\":\"9A.04f3\",\"190001250\":\"9A.04f2\",\"190001240\":\"9A.04f1\",\"190001230\":\"9A.04e9\",\"190001220\":\"9A.04e8\",\"190001190\":\"9A.04e5\",\"190001210\":\"9A.04e7\",\"190000220\":\"9A.01c6\",\"190000210\":\"9A.01c5\",\"190000200\":\"9A.01c4\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004840\":\"9A.05c3\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006900\":\"9A.05o3\"},\"\":{\"32100802\":\"210.08b\"}}'), ('817', 'Direct Instruction: Introduce Correlated Members to Set', 'There are  rules or guidelines for introducing members of a set of related items (e.g., names of letters or spelling rules).   A member is a stimulus that calls for a particular response or set of responses.  When we teach the learner to identify the letter \\\'m,\\\' we are teaching a member of the  correlated set, letter names.  In a given correlated set, there may be minimum-differences in either the features (form) of members, in the label, or both.  For example, the letters \\\'m\\\' &amp; \\\' n\\\' are minimum-difference pairs.  They are highly similar in form and label  where \\\' n\\\' and \\\'r\\\' are highly similar in form only.  The guidelines focus on teaching you how to develop instructional routines  for these highly similar members.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '[]'), ('816', 'Direct Instruction: Delivers Scripted Lesson (Formats)', 'A teacher models the response that s/he wants the learner(s) to perform (T points to a picture and says , \\\"This is a dog\\\").   A model is an antecedent in that it sets the occasion for the behavior to occur.  Next, the teacher leads the learner(s) in saying the correct response (i.e., T says, \\\"Say it with me.\\\"  \\\"A dog\\\").  If the learner(s) repeats the statement then the teacher will test by pointing to a picture &amp; saying , \\\"What is this?\\\"  Immediately correct ALL errors.  The basic correction procedure for content consists of re-teaching and retesting students.  More specifically, the steps include a MODEL, followed by a TEST and a DELAYED TEST.  Immediately after the error, the teacher: 1) models the correct answer, then 2) tests students by asking them to respond to the original task stimulus. The teacher then goes back to an earlier task, and after presenting several other items, 3) again presents the item on which the error occurred.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '[]'), ('815', 'Differential Reinforcement of  Zero Responding (DRO) ', '\\\"Differential Reinforcement of  Zero Responding\\\" is one of the schedules of reinforcement that is used to weaken repertoires.  This schedule of reinforcement, DRO, is used to \\\'eliminate\\\' responding.  For example, DRO may be used to eliminate hair pulling by putting it on a DRO schedule of reinforcement.  For example, the teacher would RESET the stop watch each time hair pulling occurs.  When a continuous five minutes of  \\\'zero hair pulling\\\' occurs then reinforcement would be delivered.  The starting schedule of reinforcement is determined by obtaining the mean intervals between instances of the targeted behaviors.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Weaken', '', '', '[]'), ('812', 'Differential Reinforcement', 'Differential reinforcement is used to get responding skilled.   The learner may repeat a word but  it could have been done \\\'better.\\\'   Differential reinforcement is often used in combination with reinforcing successive approximations of complex behavior in the contingency called  shaping.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21207052\":\"12.07e2\",\"2120802\":\"12.08b\",\"2120804\":\"12.08d\",\"2120806\":\"12.08f\",\"2120807\":\"12.08g\",\"2120808\":\"12.08h\",\"2120810\":\"12.08j\",\"2120812\":\"12.08l\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190001130\":\"9A.04d2\",\"190001120\":\"9A.04d1\",\"190001100\":\"9A.04c8\",\"190001080\":\"9A.04c6\",\"190001070\":\"9A.04c5\",\"190001030\":\"9A.04c1\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006532\":\"9A.05j1A\",\"190006536\":\"9A.05j1B\"}}'), ('813', 'Differential Reinforcement of Alternative Behaviors (DRA)', 'Some of our learners have acquired socially unacceptable behaviors for \\\'getting\\\' what they want or \\\'avoiding/escaping\\\'  what\\\'s aversive to them.  When we use DRA we are placing the undesired behavior on extinction and immediately reinforcing the acceptable \\\'alternative\\\' behaviors.  For instance, if our learner has been using \\\'crying\\\' to get what he wants, we would put \\\'crying\\\' on extinction and reinforce acceptable, alternative forms of  \\\'asking\\\' behaviors that would get him what he wants.  Essentially, what is happening is that the child will be taught a more socially acceptable way to get what he wants. One way of getting the reinforcers is replaced with an alternative way of getting the same reinforcers.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Weaken', '', '', '[]'), ('814', 'Differential Reinforcement of Low Rate Behavior (DRL)', 'The response rate must be high (e.g. talking).  Reinforcement occurs only when responding is occurring at a designated low rate.  Begin by determining the average number of  responses per an interval of time (e.g., five min.).  Once you have obtained the average number of responses, then you deliver contingent reinforcement at the end of any interval in which the number of responses is at, or below, baseline rate.  Procedure may be set up with a self-monitoring component.  Instructor\\\'s tone and manner should be as matter-of-fact and supportive as possible.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Weaken', '', '', '[]'), ('808', 'Curriculum for Naive Learners: Lesson 1-16', 'Created for the naÃ¯ve learners.  Some of these children have not had any opportunities in formal teaching, and spend very little time in the proximity of adults. They also typically do not let others know what their wants and needs are.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('809', 'Curriculum: Lesson 17-36', 'Created for our learners that missing \\\"some\\\" of the competent learner repertoires. They may listen well and work one on one, but may have some difficulty working in small group. They are getting ready for Direct instruction and other curriculum that will begin to teach to the academic standards.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('810', 'DATA COLLECTION PROCEDURES', 'Prescribed way to take data\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 5', '{\"5\":{\"150103\":\"5.01c\",\"1502072\":\"5.02g2\",\"150401\":\"5.04a\",\"1508011\":\"5.08a1\"}}'), ('811', 'Deprivation', 'The value of stimuli vary throughout the day. One of the variables that contributes to this \\\'value\\\' is deprivation.  If a learner has been denied access to a highly valued object then it is more likely to be something that he will want.  The effectiveness of potential reinforcers is affected by the availability of the reinforcer.  If a learner has NOT played with a preferred object for a couple of hours, it is likely that he will \\\'want\\\' to gain access to that object.  The opposite of deprivation is satiation.  For example, if a learner has just eaten his lunch where he drank a large bottle of juice, the value of juice is likely to have diminished for a while.  He may NOT be interested in drinking juice immediately after lunch.  Therefore, one would not offer juice as a potential reinforcer right after that lunch period.  To maintain the effectiveness of reinforcers, it is often necessary to deprive the learner of the valued stimuli.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"12\":{\"21203031\":\"12.03c 1\",\"2120401\":\"12.04a\",\"2120404\":\"12.04d\",\"2120405\":\"12.04e\",\"2120408\":\"12.04h\",\"21207031\":\"12.07c1\",\"21207032\":\"12.07c2\",\"21207044\":\"12.07d4\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000780\":\"9A.03j4\",\"190000770\":\"9A.03j3\",\"190000760\":\"9A.03j2\",\"190000750\":\"9A.03j1\",\"190000530\":\"9A.03f4\",\"190000230\":\"9A.01c7\",\"190000080\":\"9A.01a8\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006830\":\"9A.05n2\"},\"11\":{\"21108011\":\"11.08a1\"}}'), ('807', 'Cumulative Review', 'Cumulative Review routines are used to strengthen existing repertoires or firmed responses. They are  \\\'Stimulus Control\\\' operations.  They include manipulation of the antecedents and the consequences. The initial teaching sequences used to teach naÃ¯ve learners generally need more careful expansion than those presented to advanced learners.  Effective generalization routines, with cumulative review exercises, assure that the new learning is thoroughly integrated with familiar concepts and skills.   The following rules for conducting a cumulative review were taken from the book Theory of Instruction by Engelmann and Carnine (1982, page 113).  These rules apply most directly to introducing new members to a set of related items (e.g., animals and letters).\r\nA common mistake made by instructors is to review every learned item with a learner each and every day.  Cumulative review routines are designed to place a limit on the number of learned items that need to be reviewed each day.  This way more time can be focused on delivering the other routines for practicing the firmed items to expand their use in novel circumstances.\r\nDesigning Cumulative Reviews:\r\nThe most difficult part of the procedure for introducing new members to a set is the review, particularly when a large number of members has already been introduced.  To assure that each new member is presented within the context of the members that have already been taught, the review activities are designed to these five criteria:\r\n1.	The review set should contain no more than six members (If you have already taught 3 members before introducing the new members, the review set will consist of 3 members.  If have already taught 5, the review set will contain 5.  If you have taught 34, the review set will contain 6).\r\n2.	The member most similar to the new member is included in the review set.\r\n3.	The two new members most recently introduced are included in the set.\r\n4.	The new member most frequently missed during previous review exercises is included.\r\n5.	The two members that have been least frequently presented during the last three or four review exercises should also be included.\r\n', 'Instructional Routines', '', '', '{\"9b\":{\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\"},\"100\":{\"310007014\":\"100.07a4\"}}'), ('801', 'Consequential', 'The instructor may present, withhold, and/or withdrawal stimuli (e.g., object, food, or correction) following the emission of a behavior. There are three types of consequences:  Reinforcement, Extinction, and Punishment.  Refer to the contingency worksheets for an adequate treatment of each of these contingencies.\r\nSince we are most interested in developing repertoires, our focus will mostly be on reinforcement.  It is the only consequences that establishes and strengthens repertoires (i.e., ABC relations).\r\n', 'Basic Behavior Operations', '', '', '{\"2\":{\"1210013\":\"2.10a3\"},\"12\":{\"21207043\":\"12.07d3\",\"21207052\":\"12.07e2\",\"21207084\":\"12.07h4\",\"21208\":\"12.08a\",\"2121204\":\"12.12d\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000190\":\"9A.01c3\"},\"\":{\"118390\":\"2pt.10a3\"}}'), ('802', 'CONTINUOUS REINFORCEMENT', 'Reinforce \"every\" response to establish repertoires\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 4', '{\"4\":{\"140205\":\"4.02e\",\"140401\":\"4.04a\",\"140703\":\"4.07c\"},\"5\":{\"1506041\":\"5.06d1\"},\"7\":{\"170506\":\"7.05f\",\"171001\":\"7.10a\"},\"10\":{\"2101003\":\"10.10c\"},\"12\":{\"21203033\":\"12.03c3\",\"21207064\":\"12.07f4\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000520\":\"9A.03f3\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004770\":\"9A.05b6\",\"190005020\":\"9A.05f2\"}}'), ('803', 'Copy Text', 'A written verbal response to a written verbal stimulus with point-to- correspondence (writing exactly what is written).\r\n', 'Verbal Operants', '', '', '[]'), ('804', 'CORRELATING STIMULI', 'Antecedent stimuli are associated with reinforcing consequences in A-B-C relations\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 7', '{\"9A L4\":{\"190004760\":\"9A.05b5\",\"190004780\":\"9A.05b7\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006650\":\"9A.05k6a\"}}'), ('805', 'Course of Study:  Fluency Based Instruction, CLM Units 210, 220, and 230', 'The Participant will arrange and conduct a timed practice with a learner on an already established skill.  To complete the performance review checkout in Unit 210, they will: a) Conduct a timed practice to strengthen an already established skill, b) Videotape yourself conducting the timed practice, c) Evaluate your performance, and d) Explain to your coach what you may need to do differently, if you made any errors in conducting the timed practice. In Unit 220, the participants will learn to read 6 cycle celeration graphs.  In Unit 230, the participants will learn to chart on celeration 6 cycle graphs.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('806', 'Course of Study:  Introductory CLM Unit', 'Each participant in the CLM Course of Study will be assigned a \\\'certified\\\' CLM Coach. Primarily, we (i.e., CLM Coach) are expected to assist you and other instructors to be the \\\'best instructors\\\' you can be.  We are committed to assisting you in performing successfully and applying what you learn in the CLM Units. At any point in time, we will be responsive to your requests for assistance. We are determined to make this experience a very productive one for you and your learner.  With your CLM Coach\\\'s assistance, you will be expected to do the following for your \\\'performance review checkout\\\' on the Introductory CLM Unit: a) Begin each CLM Unit in a timely manner, b) Answer all questions and fill out all required worksheets in your CLM Course of Study Binders, c) Contact your CLM \\\'certified\\\' Coach to checkout on a CLM Unit, d) By being the best instructor you can be, apply what you learned with your chosen learner in your learning environments and, e) Request the next CLM Unit once you master a unit.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('799', 'Conditioning ', 'In the first phase, the learner will be taught that as soon as he performs as expected he will be given a token to immediately exchange for a variety of potential reinforcers.  During this phase, it is best to arrange to exchange the token as quickly as possible and as often as possible.  It is important to associate the token with immediate access to a variety of potential reinforcers (i.e., the shorter the task requirement the better).  In this second phase, the learner will be taught that he will have to do a little bit more to get each token.  However, once he receives the second token he will immediately exchange them for a variety of potential reinforcers.  During this phase, you will lean the schedule of reinforcement ASAP.  In this third and last phase, the learner is taught to operate on a more delayed schedule of reinforcement.   This will assure that the learner can wait for longer and longer periods of time before he exchanges (i.e., cashes in) his tokens for the back-up reinforcers.   Such intermittent schedules of reinforcement are arranged to maintain responding (refer to the \\\'Schedules of Reinforcement\\\' contingency for additional details).  Over time the learner will complete entire lessons before you will have to mark his card or give him a penny to place on his card.  Cashing in the pennies can be delayed for longer and longer periods of time.   Must go about this process very gradually.   Remember to provide a variety of back-up reinforcers to maintain the effectiveness of the tokens.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"7\":{\"170102\":\"7.01b\",\"170103\":\"7.01c\",\"1705072\":\"7.05g2\",\"1706023\":\"7.06b3\",\"1706042\":\"7.06d2\",\"170702\":\"7.07b\",\"1709011\":\"7.09a1\",\"1709021\":\"7.09b1\",\"1710031\":\"7.10c1\",\"171103\":\"7.11c\",\"1711051\":\"7.11e1\",\"1711052\":\"7.11e2\"},\"9b\":{\"1906022\":\"9.06b2\"}