,\"21207086\":\"12.07h6\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000650\":\"9A.03h1\",\"190000230\":\"9A.01c7\",\"190000170\":\"9A.01c1\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004760\":\"9A.05b5\",\"190004770\":\"9A.05b6\",\"190004780\":\"9A.05b7\",\"190005100\":\"9A.05g7\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006640\":\"9A.05k5\",\"190006750\":\"9A.05m1\",\"190006970\":\"9A.05p2B\",\"190007060\":\"9A.05p8B\"},\"\":{\"118290\":\"2pt.09a2\",\"118300\":\"2pt.09a3\",\"118380\":\"2pt.10a2\",\"118400\":\"2pt.10a4\"}}'), ('796', 'CONDITIONING HISTORY', 'Potentially reinforcing and aversive stimuli for a learner\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 12', '{\"12\":{\"2120401\":\"12.04a\",\"2120403\":\"12.04c\",\"21205012\":\"12.05a2\",\"21205022\":\"12.05b2\"}}'), ('797', 'Conditioning Neutral Stimuli As Conditioned Reinforcing Stimuli', 'A stimulus is called a conditioned reinforcer if it is not originally reinforcing (had neutral value), but acquires reinforcing properties through pairing or correlating  it with a stimulus that IS reinforcing.  Stimuli that are usually \\\'naturally\\\' reinforcing (such as candy  or other edibles) are called unconditioned or primary reinforcers.  Primary reinforcers are often paired or correlated with neutral stimuli to create conditioned reinforcing stimuli.  The critical component is to choose neutral stimuli (e.g., Praise or Tokens) that are readily available and easy to deliver.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '[]'), ('798', 'Conditioning ', 'In the first phase, the learner will be taught that as soon as he performs as expected he will be given a token to immediately exchange for a variety of potential reinforcers.  During this phase, it is best to arrange to exchange the token as quickly as possible and as often as possible.  It is important to associate the token with immediate access to a variety of potential reinforcers (i.e., the shorter the task requirement the better).  In this second phase, the learner will be taught that he will have to do a little bit more to get each token.  However, once he receives the second token he will immediately exchange them for a variety of potential reinforcers.  During this phase, you will lean the schedule of reinforcement ASAP.  In this third and last phase, the learner is taught to operate on a more delayed schedule of reinforcement.   This will assure that the learner can wait for longer and longer periods of time before he exchanges (i.e., cashes in) his tokens for the back-up reinforcers.   Such intermittent schedules of reinforcement are arranged to maintain responding (refer to contingency \\\'Schedules of Reinforcement for additional details). Over time, the learner will complete entire lessons before you will have to mark his card or give him a penny to place on his card.  Cashing in the pennies can be delayed for longer and longer periods of time.   Must go about this process very gradually.   Remember to provide a variety of back-up reinforcers to maintain the effectiveness of the tokens.\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"7\":{\"170102\":\"7.01b\",\"170103\":\"7.01c\",\"1705072\":\"7.05g2\",\"1706023\":\"7.06b3\",\"1706042\":\"7.06d2\",\"170702\":\"7.07b\",\"1709011\":\"7.09a1\",\"1709021\":\"7.09b1\",\"1710031\":\"7.10c1\",\"171103\":\"7.11c\",\"1711051\":\"7.11e1\",\"1711052\":\"7.11e2\"},\"9b\":{\"1906022\":\"9.06b2\"},\"12\":{\"2120401\":\"12.04a\",\"2120403\":\"12.04c\",\"2120406\":\"12.04f\",\"21205012\":\"12.05a2\",\"21205022\":\"12.05b2\",\"21207037\":\"12.07c7\",\"21207047\":\"12.07d7\",\"21207057\":\"12.07e7\",\"21207073\":\"12.07g3\",\"21207086\":\"12.07h6\"},\"100\":{\"310009013\":\"100.09a3\"},\"9A1-3\":{\"190000970\":\"9A.04b4\",\"190000830\":\"9A.03k4\",\"190000730\":\"9A.03i5\",\"190000670\":\"9A.03h3\",\"190000660\":\"9A.03h2\",\"190000450\":\"9A.03e5\",\"190000460\":\"9A.03e6\",\"190000410\":\"9A.03e1\",\"190000170\":\"9A.01c1\",\"190000160\":\"9A.01b7\"},\"9A L4\":{\"190004760\":\"9A.05b5\",\"190004800\":\"9A.05b9\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006560\":\"9A.05j3\",\"190006570\":\"9A.05j4\",\"190006660\":\"9A.05k6b\",\"190006680\":\"9A.05k8\",\"190006830\":\"9A.05n2\"}}'), ('795', 'CONDITIONED REINFORCERS', 'Neutral stimuli conditioned as potential reinforcers\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 7', '{\"7\":{\"1705043\":\"7.05d3\",\"1706051\":\"7.06e1\",\"171001\":\"7.10a\",\"1710031\":\"7.10c1\",\"1710042\":\"7.10d2\"},\"11\":{\"211050131\":\"11.05a3B\"},\"12\":{\"21207023\":\"12.07b3\",\"21207033\":\"12.07c3\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006780\":\"9A.05m4\"}}'), ('792', 'Collaborative Consultation: Worksheets Designing Contingencies', 'This manual will provide assistance to educators and parents to make conspicuous the contingencies operating in a given situation.  It is a companion to Unit 12: Delivers Supplementary Reinforcement Contingencies as Prescribed.  An ongoing functional analysis is conducted which enables the board certified behavior analyst (BCBA) to work with the participant to determine what rearrangements of the contingencies might assure for the development of the CLRs and the weakening of undesirable repertoires.  This product contains a \\\'CheatSheet\\\' to assist the participants in selecting possible contingencies to affect change in behavior with the assistance of their BCBA. Once the contingencies are selected they are arranged and rearranged until the expected outcomes are produced.  Each contingency worksheet (e.g., Premack) contains a brief description, likely effects, type of programming, warnings  when using the contingency, guidelines with space to individualize per learner. Throughout the consultation process the behavior analyst (BCBA) recognizes that the real expertise with learner in each situation lies with the educators and parents who live with the learner each and every day.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('793', 'CONCEPT', 'Members of a class of objects, actions, or events\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 9', '{\"0\":{\"1001032\":\"0.01c2\",\"1001034\":\"0.01c4\"},\"2\":{\"1203022\":\"2.03b2\"},\"8\":{\"180801\":\"8.08a\"},\"9b\":{\"1901032\":\"9.01c2\",\"1901034\":\"9.01c4\",\"1901036\":\"9.01c6\",\"1901037\":\"9.01c7\",\"1901038\":\"9.01c8\",\"1901039\":\"9.01c9\",\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\",\"190105302\":\"9.01e3b\",\"1901055\":\"9.01e5\",\"1901056\":\"9.01e6\",\"1901057\":\"9.01e7\",\"1901061\":\"9.01f1\",\"1901062\":\"9.01f2\",\"1901063\":\"9.01f3\",\"1901071\":\"9.01g1\",\"1901091\":\"9.01i1\",\"1901094\":\"9.01i4\",\"1901103\":\"9.01j3\",\"1901105\":\"9.01j5\",\"1901111\":\"9.01k1\",\"1901112\":\"9.01k2\",\"1901121\":\"9.01l1\",\"1901122\":\"9.01l2\",\"1902011\":\"9.02a1\",\"1903022\":\"9.03b2\",\"1903023\":\"9.03b3\",\"1903032\":\"9.03c2\",\"1903033\":\"9.03c3\",\"1903034\":\"9.03c4\",\"1903036\":\"9.03c6\",\"1903037\":\"9.03c7\",\"1905011\":\"9.05a1\",\"190601\":\"9.06a\",\"1906022\":\"9.06b2\"},\"10\":{\"2100102\":\"10.01b\",\"2100802\":\"10.08b\"},\"\":{\"6040912\":\"DI_1.2\",\"60409196\":\"DI_1.96\",\"80409221\":\"DI_221\",\"118180\":\"2pt.03b2\"}}'), ('794', 'Conditioned Reinforcers', 'In order to establish new repertoires one must be able deliver the consequences immediately as dictated by the schedule of reinforcement.   The availability of conditioned reinforcers provides one with the ability to present the stimuli quickly.  That is, the learner gets a  valued stimulus immediately following the  performance of the targeted behavior or series of consecutive responses.  One maintains the  effectiveness of conditioned reinforcers by repeatedly pairing or correlating  them with the primary  reinforcers (e.g., juice) or other conditioned reinforcers (e.g., free-choice time).\r\n', 'Contingencies to Develop', '', '', '{\"7\":{\"1705043\":\"7.05d3\",\"1706051\":\"7.06e1\",\"171001\":\"7.10a\",\"1710031\":\"7.10c1\",\"1710042\":\"7.10d2\"},\"11\":{\"211050131\":\"11.05a3B\"},\"12\":{\"21207023\":\"12.07b3\",\"21207033\":\"12.07c3\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006780\":\"9A.05m4\"}}'), ('791', ' CLM Team Management Process', 'The Team Management binder contains a set of Action Management Worksheets that list the actions to be completed to review the performance of the CLM Team (e.g., coach, behavior specialist, and parents).  The CLM Coordinators uses the forms in the binder to \\\'remind\\\' them of the critical actions required and who is responsible from team meeting to team meeting. For example, it contains worksheets to track the list of actions required to develop or weaken repertoires.  A Case Review Process for formulating programming is also a critical feature of the team review process.   The Coordinator will review the contents of the Learner\\\'s folder to assure that all required forms are in place and contain the data to determine the status of the learner\\\'s performance.  At each Team Meeting, the Coordinator or representative can review the status of the actions that need to be completed for a successful implementation of the CLModel for a learner. The binder also contains checklist to review the performance of the CLM Coach to assure for the application of what is learned in the CLM Units.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('790', 'CLM Curricula: Lessons 1-16, 9-36, and 1-33', 'The CLM Curriculum has been developed to provide detailed instructional formats that are designed to systematically strengthen the seven Competent Learner Repertoires (CLRs) of Talking, Listening, Problem Solving, Observing, Participating, Reading and Writing.  It consists of two levels that take the naive learner from CLRs that are not established to the establishment and maintenance of all seven CLRs across all appropriate situations.  The completion of the second level of the CLM Curriculum prepares learners to be successful in validated curricula at the kindergarten or beginning first grade level of sophistication for normally developing children.  Routine implementation of the CLMs instructional formats has been shown to be associated with the development of the CLRs.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]');
INSERT INTO `glossary` VALUES ('788', 'CLM Course of Study for Coaching: CLM Unit 100', 'Coaching is utilized to assure for mastery of the educators\\\' and parents\\\' CLM Course of Study units and the eventual oversight of the arranging and re-arranging of the instructional conditions.  The trained CLM Coaches are governed by the Personalized System of Instruction guidelines (e.g. Tutor as needed and Pace progress) as they monitor their educators\\\' and parents\\\' performance..  The CLModel places heavy emphasis on developing the instructional staff\\\'s repertoires to perform instructional \\\"tasks\\\" that will produce competent learners. The intent of the CLM Training Process is twofold: 1) Bring educators (i.e., teachers, instructional assistants, or parents) to mastery of the process of repertoire development and 2) Motivate educators to engage in performing the instructional tasks required to develop repertoires.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('789', 'CLM Course of Study Unit 1-8, 9-10', 'In the CLM Units 1-8 the participants (i.e., educators and parents).   Initially, the participants select a naÃ¯ve learner and begin to formulate, deliver, and monitor programming as they master and apply what they have learned.  They begin by assessing some of their learner\\\'s repertoires.  Next, they deliver lessons to develop the \\\'missing\\\' competent learner repertoires.   Next, they learn to report factually the behaviors and events that occur in instructional conditions.   Next, they learn that they can develop the Competent Learner Repertoires (CLRs) and weaken undesirable repertoires. The CLM Units are sequenced so that as the participants progress they develop the next part of the programming that would be naturally required to develop and/or weaken repertoire.   The CLM Units are delivered on  CD-ROMs so that participants are able to complete each course of study at their own pace and leisure.   A CLM Coach conducts Performance Reviews to assure for mastery of content and application of material learned.\r\nIn CLM Unit 8, the participant learn to use a \\\'placement test\\\' to determine the entry lesson for his learner in the CLM curricula (i.e., CLM Lessons 1, 4, 8, 12, 17, or 21) or placement in an alternative validated curriculum (e.g., SRA\\\'s Language for Learning Lessons 1, 11, 21, 31, or 41), track and monitor the learners\\\' progress in these lessons, and determine when to progress to a new lesson.\r\nIn CLM Unit 9, the participants learn to deliver a Teacher-directed format (part of a lesson). Instructors are provided with the design principles in order to understand how formats are designed.  There are two CLM Unit 9s, 9A and 9B. Unit 9A is designed to prepare instructor to develop the repertoires for the naÃ¯ve learners.  Unit 9B is designed for the more advanced naÃ¯ve learners.\r\nIn CLM Unit 10, the participants will learn to answer a pivotal question, \\\"What is the source of reinforcement that is maintaining behavior?\\\".  This begin the process of formulating programming to develop desired repertoires  and weaken undesired  repertoires\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('777', 'Application', 'Application routines are used to determine if a repertoire is IN STRENGTH.  It is also a stimulus control operation, but in most cases, you are not expected to control for all the variables that may interfere with the learner\\\'s performance.  An instructor arranges the context (e.g., Functional Action - Maintain Setting) to see if the learner uses the repertoire(s) as expected.  You would select a particular set of actions (e.g., setting the table) that you expect the learner to perform in the chosen context.  For example, a pre-1 learner would only be expected to imitate a single-step action while a level 3 learner would be expected to imitate a series of three actions to learn to set the table.\r\nAn instructor provides the least amount of assistance necessary for the learner to apply what he has learned. You are encouraged to use \\\'priming\\\' (telling the learner exactly what to do or say) if the learner can imitate or respond echoically.  If you MUST use prompting be sure and FADE the prompt(s) as quickly as possible within the session.  If you cannot fade the prompt(s) within the session, you may question if the learner\\\'s repertoires is in strength enough to use it in this application routine.  You may need to return to another type of instructional routine (e.g., Generalization).\r\nYou should set the occasion (context) for your learner to USE the new strengthened repertoire in as many \\\'real\\\' life situations as possible.  You are encouraged to apply the competent learner repertoire(s) in at least one of the Day-to-Day contexts:  1) Functional Actions (i.e., Communication, Socialize, Entertain, Maintain Health, Purchase, Maintain Setting, Nourish Self, Transport, and Earn a Living). Or 2) USE of \\\'Tool\\\' (i.e., Object, Hand, Reference, Power), or 3) Subject Matter (i.e., Performing Arts, Movement, Science, Language Arts, Social Studies, Health, Math, and Visual Arts).\r\nThese \\\'Real\\\' life situations (context) will provide the learner with opportunities to use one or a combination of repertoires (adduction). That is, you may expect your learner to use his Problem solver (mand) and Participator (peer-directed) repertoires to perform a desired task in novel circumstances.  For example, if an instructor chose the Functional Action, Entertain, and select the action of playing with a peer, the learner would be expected to ask a peer to swing with him at neighborhood playground.   Application routines help learners become more independent and adaptive to situations they may not have experienced before.  Skinner refers to this behavior as \\\'self-reliant\\\' behavior (Technology of Teaching, 1968).\r\nWe want the learner to function as independently as possible. For example, if the learner has acquired the problem solver (mand) repertoire, make sure that he uses it to purchase an item in a grocery store.  Set the learner up to ask (problem solver -mand) for a preferred item.  If he has learned to participate in a non-directed condition, have him entertain himself at friend\\\'s house.  If he as learned to participate in a peer-directed condition, take him to a playground so that he can socialize with his neighborhood peers.\r\n', 'Instructional Routines', '', '', '{\"9b\":{\"1901051\":\"9.01e1\"},\"11\":{\"21106012\":\"11.06a2\",\"21109032\":\"11.09c2\"}}'), ('787', 'CLM Course of Studies (COS): CLM Units  11-12', 'In Unit 11, the participants are expected to formulate programming by answering two of the four questions:  1.  What repertoires will be developed or weakened? and 2. Are there adequate stimuli to affect change?  As you are delivering the programming, you will collect data on at least four repertoires.  Their CLM Coach will assist them in selecting the \\\'type of data\\\' to collect per repertoire.  Within one week of delivering the programming, they will be expected to begin to \\\'conduct a progress review\\\' of their learners\\\' performance across each of the repertoires. At that time they will begin to make the following instructional decisions:  continue it (lesson or step) as is,  revise it, discontinue it, or move to the next lesson or step, if criteria are met.\r\nIn Unit 12, with your CLM Coach\\\'s assistance, you will continue to formulate programming for your learner by answering the third of the four formulation questions: What contingencies will be delivered given the type of programming required to develop and or weaken the repertoires.?  You goal is to: Delivery the supplementary contingencies as prescribed.  In Unit 12, you will be expected to: 1) Study the existing contingencies to decide what you may need to do or say to develop/weaken repertoires based on \\\'best practice\\\' guidelines (contingencies) with the assistance of your CLM Coach; 2) Determine the type(s) of programming required to develop repertoires; 3) Describe the basic behavioral operations for each contingency; 4) Select the most appropriate contingencies to develop your learners\\\'  missing repertoires; and 5) Adhere to the \\\'guidelines\\\' of the contingencies unless you observe that the learner\\\'s current performance warrants otherwise.\r\n', 'CLM Products', '', '', '[]'), ('786', 'CLM Coordinator Manual', 'The Coordinators\\\' Manual delineates the CLM Coordinator\\\'s Key Responsibilities in implementing the CLModel.  The coordinator is responsible for assuring for success in programming for the implementers (e.g., instructors, administrators, and parents) as well as the learners. These are six key responsibilities for CLM Coordinators: 1) Adhere to CLM Policies and Procedures, 2) Supervise Team Members Face to Face, 3) Manage the Implementation Team, 4) Perform Formative Evaluations 5) Conduct Action Management Process, and 6) Perform Unanticipated Administrative Tasks.\r\n', '', '', '', '[]'), ('781', 'BACK-UP REINFORCERS', 'Valued reinforcers purchased with tokens\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 7', '{\"7\":{\"170904\":\"7.09d\",\"171001\":\"7.10a\"},\"12\":{\"21207033\":\"12.07c3\"},\"9A L5-7\":{\"190006570\":\"9A.05j4\"}}'), ('782', 'BASIC BEHAVIORAL OPERATIONS', 'Manipulations of elements of the contingencies\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 12', '{\"12\":{\"2120104\":\"12.01d\",\"21207023\":\"12.07b3\",\"21207043\":\"12.07d3\",\"2121202\":\"12.12b\",\"2121204\":\"12.12d\"}}'), ('783', 'BEHAVIOR', 'Any actions a person may perform\r\n', 'FLUENCY CARDS', '', 'Unit 10', '{\"0\":{\"1001011\":\"0.01a1\",\"1001022\":\"0.01b2\",\"1001023\":\"0.01b3\",\"1002041\":\"0.02d1\",\"1002042\":\"0.02d2\",\"1003021\":\"0.03b1\",\"1003022\":\"0.03b2\",\"100303\":\"0.03c\",\"100305\":\"0.03e\",\"1004011\":\"0.04a1\",\"1001012\":\"0.01a2\"},\"1\":{\"110101\":\"1.01a\",\"110701\":\"1.07a\",\"1108\":\"1.08\",\"1111011\":\"1.11a1\",\"1111012\":\"1.11a2\",\"11120